WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.020 --> 00:00:01.160
Good morning, everyone.

2
00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:06.090
Thank you for coming to this session on advances in glioblastoma research and

3
00:00:06.140 --> 00:00:07.180
experimental therapies.

4
00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:11.380
If you're here, you're already done the hardest part, which is finding the room.

5
00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:12.240
So well done.

6
00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:18.300
As you know, I'm sure many of you in the audience, I recognize many

7
00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:21.220
faces, you're very familiar with the challenges of gliomas

8
00:00:21.260 --> 00:00:25.240
and brain cancer in general. We're going to try to highlight

9
00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:28.370
some of those challenges. They're a little bit different types of cancer than other

10
00:00:28.420 --> 00:00:28.800
organs.

11
00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:33.390
We're going to discuss how they're integrated with the central nervous system

12
00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:36.560
parenchyma, how they're forming interconnected network.

13
00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:40.690
We're going to discuss some of the unique features of the microenvironment, and

14
00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:44.129
then also discuss some of the unique aspects of their molecular

15
00:00:44.180 --> 00:00:48.020
heterogeneity. So to cover all these aspects, we have four speakers, and

16
00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:52.000
our first one is Varun Venkataramani from Heidelberg University,

17
00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:54.600
who will be discussing about

18
00:00:55.860 --> 00:00:58.720
integration of glioblastoma into neural network.

19
00:01:00.660 --> 00:01:02.380
Yes. Thank you so much, Mario, and

20
00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:06.960
I want to thank you and all the organizers for giving me the opportunity here to

21
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.820
talk here today about our research on brain tumor networks, as

22
00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:14.720
well as neural mechanisms that drive glioblastoma.

23
00:01:15.560 --> 00:01:18.780
I have no disclosures. And I want to start off by

24
00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:21.400
basically a historic slide,

25
00:01:22.700 --> 00:01:25.760
which I got from Nick Castro from MGH,

26
00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:30.000
highlighting basically the challenges of glioblastoma, because I was always under

27
00:01:30.020 --> 00:01:34.000
the impression that we have been bad at treating glioblastoma in

28
00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:35.680
the last three to four decades,

29
00:01:36.740 --> 00:01:40.240
when learning that we've actually been bad at treating this disease

30
00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.680
for more than 100 years here, when it was still called

31
00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:48.140
with a different name, spongioblastoma multiforme, and when you look at the

32
00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:49.340
survival times,

33
00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:53.460
nothing much has really changed in these 100 years.

34
00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:59.140
So what makes these brain tumors so incurable from our points of view?

35
00:01:59.280 --> 00:01:59.880
So basically,

36
00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:02.780
these tumors are a whole brain disease.

37
00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:06.280
You see here an autopsy section of a patient with an IDH mutant

38
00:02:06.740 --> 00:02:10.620
astrocytoma. And you see basically in the brown color here, the main

39
00:02:10.640 --> 00:02:11.240
tumor mass

40
00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:16.020
and where all these black dots indicate where you can find tumor cells

41
00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:19.800
throughout the entire brain, which makes it clear that you cannot surgically

42
00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:21.380
resect the entire tumor.

43
00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:26.060
The remaining parts are resistant towards standard of care treatment

44
00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:27.480
with chemo and radiotherapy,

45
00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:32.340
and basically no targeted therapy has been really successful in the

46
00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:33.460
last decades.

47
00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:37.829
So what we think is that we have to really rethink also how we

48
00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:41.120
study tumors in the brain, because simply

49
00:02:41.800 --> 00:02:45.700
taking treatments from tumors outside the brain and applying them for

50
00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:49.090
brain tumors has not worked out. So we need to understand tumors in their

51
00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:50.000
microenvironment.

52
00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:53.820
And when really studying these tumors in their

53
00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:57.850
intricate communication with the central nervous

54
00:02:57.920 --> 00:03:01.820
system, what you find is that these tumor cells are basically not

55
00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:05.740
alone, but that they're really communicating with the central nervous system.

56
00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:09.560
And what we found one of first experiments when looking at these

57
00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:13.320
connections between the nervous system and brain tumors, is that they are

58
00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:17.340
actually synaptic contacts on a portion of these

59
00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:20.280
tumor cells here looked at with electron microscopy.

60
00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:24.850
So we stained tumor cells with a tumor specific marker, which makes them

61
00:03:24.900 --> 00:03:25.640
DAB

62
00:03:26.480 --> 00:03:29.520
positive and showing here in an electron dense fashion.

63
00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:33.040
And when you really look at the ultra structure, you see synaptic vesicles from a

64
00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:35.800
neuron, a synaptic cleft, a synaptic density.

65
00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.740
So all hallmarks of bona fide synapses that are

66
00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:43.260
connecting from neurons to these tumor cells.

67
00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:47.280
And we find this both in patient or xenograft models, but also

68
00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:50.140
in material from patients.

69
00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:54.800
So this led us to the model that there are unidirectional

70
00:03:54.820 --> 00:03:57.010
synaptic inputs to tumor cells

71
00:03:57.820 --> 00:04:01.360
that then lead to measurable electrophysiological currents that get

72
00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:05.380
translated into calcium events in these tumor cells that then lead to the

73
00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:08.520
proliferation and invasion of tumor cells.

74
00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:11.300
And these findings were already

75
00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:15.560
translated into a clinical phase

76
00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:19.579
one, two trial, the PERSECH trial, where we'd use perampanel to

77
00:04:19.721 --> 00:04:23.540
disconnect tumors from their neurons using a

78
00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:27.360
non-competitive AMPA receptor antagonist, which we usually use for

79
00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:31.040
therapy-resistant epilepsy. And the primary endpoints in this

80
00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:34.540
trial are basically based on an RNA Seq

81
00:04:34.580 --> 00:04:38.340
connectivity score, as well as AI-based MRI growth dynamics.

82
00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:43.120
I think it's clear that we also need to understand on a really

83
00:04:43.400 --> 00:04:45.080
ultra structural basis

84
00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:49.060
what really happens when we give patients this perampanel.

85
00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:52.400
So I think it's important that we also further develop

86
00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:55.700
bespoke translation readouts for neuronal

87
00:04:55.800 --> 00:04:58.100
connectivity in glioblastoma patients.

88
00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:03.400
And to do so, and to really also trace these neuron to

89
00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.240
tumor networks across

90
00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:10.160
the entire brain, which is simply not easily possible

91
00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:14.140
by simply using patch clamp electrophysiology or

92
00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:16.599
ultra structural characterization.

93
00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:20.070
We thought about adapting another technology from

94
00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:23.870
neuroscience, basically rabies-based retrograde tracing for

95
00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:24.920
these brain tumors.

96
00:05:25.750 --> 00:05:29.640
And what happens here is we infect these tumor cells with a

97
00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:33.260
pseudotyped rabies virus that then can jump

98
00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:36.500
monosynaptically to presynaptically connected

99
00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:40.320
neurons. And when doing so, what you can visualize

100
00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:44.400
are the dynamics of how connectivity forms in

101
00:05:44.420 --> 00:05:48.040
these brain tumor cells. And you see basically here in the white color

102
00:05:49.300 --> 00:05:53.020
the tumor cells that are invading and proliferating, and all

103
00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:55.580
these green cells are lighting up in the mer...

104
00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:59.920
Let's basically say within 100 hours, you see how

105
00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:02.950
almost all neurons light up that are getting

106
00:06:03.100 --> 00:06:04.840
connected

107
00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:06.860
with these tumor cells,

108
00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:11.180
showing basically that this is a dynamic phenomenon, that they are transient

109
00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:15.236
synaptic contacts, and that they are widespreadWhen you look

110
00:06:15.276 --> 00:06:19.156
at this from a whole brain perspective and map basically these

111
00:06:19.236 --> 00:06:23.156
tumors to the entire brain and their connected neurons, what you can see is

112
00:06:23.256 --> 00:06:27.056
even when the tumor is here in a very local part of the brain,

113
00:06:28.756 --> 00:06:31.476
you see basically this dense green rim around it.

114
00:06:31.536 --> 00:06:34.036
This is the proximal neuronal connectome.

115
00:06:34.566 --> 00:06:38.376
But you see also all these green signals throughout the entire brain, even on the

116
00:06:38.436 --> 00:06:42.176
contralateral side, which makes it clear that even if the tumor is

117
00:06:42.256 --> 00:06:46.176
local, the brain tumor is brain-wide

118
00:06:46.576 --> 00:06:49.956
simply by proxy, by its connectome of connected

119
00:06:50.036 --> 00:06:50.576
neurons.

120
00:06:52.396 --> 00:06:56.056
When looking at specific circuits again, and here we looked at the

121
00:06:56.136 --> 00:06:59.936
rationale of understanding the basal forebrain connections,

122
00:07:00.016 --> 00:07:03.376
which is amazingly acetylcholine-ergic, and looking at

123
00:07:03.436 --> 00:07:07.416
connected cortical areas, what we could find is

124
00:07:07.456 --> 00:07:11.216
that there are also other neurotransmitters besides glutamate that

125
00:07:11.316 --> 00:07:15.126
seem to play a role for driving glioblastoma invasion and

126
00:07:15.126 --> 00:07:18.196
proliferation. We could see that when you co-culture

127
00:07:18.735 --> 00:07:22.516
cholinergic neurons with tumor cells, again, their invasion

128
00:07:22.656 --> 00:07:24.576
speed increases as well as their proliferation.

129
00:07:24.616 --> 00:07:28.596
And when you look at circuit-specific tumor cells

130
00:07:28.876 --> 00:07:32.836
that are connected with the basal forebrain, you can see that if you knock

131
00:07:32.916 --> 00:07:36.676
down a certain muscarinergic subunit, that overall

132
00:07:36.736 --> 00:07:40.536
tumor development in that particular cortex area

133
00:07:40.596 --> 00:07:44.016
significantly also decreases, which makes it clear that we need to

134
00:07:44.066 --> 00:07:47.466
understand also these cancer in a circuit-specific manner.

135
00:07:49.596 --> 00:07:52.976
So we talked a lot about neuron to tumor synaptic

136
00:07:53.116 --> 00:07:53.776
connections.

137
00:07:54.586 --> 00:07:57.796
What we're beginning to understand over the last 10 years is that there are more

138
00:07:57.836 --> 00:08:01.556
and more also other types of tumor networks, that there are

139
00:08:01.596 --> 00:08:05.076
tumor cells that are connecting other tumor cells via gap junctions

140
00:08:05.396 --> 00:08:09.216
and tunneling nanotubes. But there are also gap junctions between

141
00:08:09.276 --> 00:08:10.996
astrocytes and tumor cells.

142
00:08:12.836 --> 00:08:16.656
Focusing on these other types of networks, we sought to

143
00:08:16.696 --> 00:08:19.596
understand how basically the molecular

144
00:08:19.656 --> 00:08:22.786
heterogeneity of cancer cells as well as their

145
00:08:22.836 --> 00:08:24.915
connectivity is interconnected.

146
00:08:24.956 --> 00:08:28.916
And for this purpose, we again were able to leverage

147
00:08:28.976 --> 00:08:32.545
and separate paradigm from neuroscience using a

148
00:08:32.576 --> 00:08:36.096
functional imaging dye called S111, usually

149
00:08:36.256 --> 00:08:39.856
used in neuroscience to label astroglia.

150
00:08:40.836 --> 00:08:44.676
And we knew beforehand that the portion of tumor cells

151
00:08:44.736 --> 00:08:48.716
take up this dye, indicating astrocytic

152
00:08:48.756 --> 00:08:52.346
and intertumoral connectivity, whereas another

153
00:08:52.356 --> 00:08:55.456
portion of these tumor cells did not take up this dye.

154
00:08:56.866 --> 00:09:00.856
We could leverage neuroscience technologies such as in vivo time-lapse

155
00:09:00.876 --> 00:09:04.436
imaging, looking live at these two tumor cell

156
00:09:04.476 --> 00:09:08.376
subpopulations in the living mouse brain and studying glioma cell

157
00:09:08.556 --> 00:09:11.616
invasion. And on the other hand, we're able to

158
00:09:11.716 --> 00:09:15.116
also leverage single cell RNA sequencing

159
00:09:15.596 --> 00:09:19.136
and beforehand FACS sorting these two populations

160
00:09:19.656 --> 00:09:23.156
and integrating basically the molecular heterogeneity with a

161
00:09:23.216 --> 00:09:24.336
functional outcome.

162
00:09:25.516 --> 00:09:27.476
And when doing so, what we could see

163
00:09:28.376 --> 00:09:32.016
is that these tumor cells that are not connected with other tumor

164
00:09:32.096 --> 00:09:32.556
cells,

165
00:09:34.376 --> 00:09:37.526
those are the ones that are from the molecular phenotype,

166
00:09:37.896 --> 00:09:41.616
neuronal-like NPC and OPC-like related.

167
00:09:41.656 --> 00:09:44.946
Whereas those tumor cells that are connected with each other

168
00:09:45.536 --> 00:09:49.476
and/or astrocytes are much more reflected in the mesenchymal and

169
00:09:49.596 --> 00:09:53.116
AC-like molecular subtypes, which again are in

170
00:09:53.176 --> 00:09:56.376
turn much more resistant towards standard of care therapy.

171
00:09:57.276 --> 00:10:01.136
When looking further into these phenotypes, what we could see is that these

172
00:10:01.216 --> 00:10:04.756
unconnected tumor cells

173
00:10:04.796 --> 00:10:08.045
resemble really immature neurons during neurodevelopment,

174
00:10:08.196 --> 00:10:12.096
featuring their neural mechanisms, and again, also via

175
00:10:12.116 --> 00:10:15.896
transient synapses are able then to invade into the

176
00:10:15.916 --> 00:10:16.216
brain.

177
00:10:18.036 --> 00:10:21.356
When looking at a completely different

178
00:10:22.536 --> 00:10:26.216
tumor entity, looking here basically at supratentorial ependymoma.

179
00:10:26.296 --> 00:10:28.396
This is work we've been doing together with Mariella

180
00:10:29.556 --> 00:10:33.316
Philbin, who has led this work and really led us into this

181
00:10:33.356 --> 00:10:37.116
tumor entity. When doing so, what we could see is that there's

182
00:10:37.156 --> 00:10:40.116
also a lot of morphological

183
00:10:40.196 --> 00:10:41.216
heterogeneity

184
00:10:42.296 --> 00:10:46.136
that again, can be related to the molecular atlas that she

185
00:10:46.456 --> 00:10:50.336
developed, that we can overlay with these different types of morphology, and in the

186
00:10:50.416 --> 00:10:53.596
end, also can see that again, also in

187
00:10:53.636 --> 00:10:57.296
supratentorial ependymoma, a neuronal-like

188
00:10:57.356 --> 00:11:00.316
subpopulation is the one that drives

189
00:11:00.376 --> 00:11:04.096
invasion into the brain. So basically also resembling,

190
00:11:04.336 --> 00:11:08.296
again, the work that we did in glioblastoma and showing again that

191
00:11:08.316 --> 00:11:10.976
is another pediatric tumor entity.

192
00:11:12.736 --> 00:11:16.016
When looking now into the subcellular

193
00:11:16.056 --> 00:11:19.336
mechanisms and really understanding whether these neuronal

194
00:11:19.436 --> 00:11:22.676
mechanisms are also reflected on a

195
00:11:22.756 --> 00:11:23.796
subcellular level,

196
00:11:24.656 --> 00:11:28.276
we were again turning to neuroscience and wanting to understand,

197
00:11:29.096 --> 00:11:32.756
do these neurite-like protrusions in these

198
00:11:32.796 --> 00:11:34.896
tumor cells follow the same

199
00:11:35.736 --> 00:11:39.616
playbook as axonal growth cones during

200
00:11:39.636 --> 00:11:43.436
neuronal migration? And there in these

201
00:11:43.456 --> 00:11:46.896
neuronal growth cones, local translation of

202
00:11:47.016 --> 00:11:50.616
mRNAs is a major deciding factor in

203
00:11:50.676 --> 00:11:51.636
really guiding

204
00:11:53.016 --> 00:11:56.856
neurons to the place where the neurites need to go.

205
00:11:56.936 --> 00:12:00.816
And when we looked in our tumor cells, again, here,

206
00:12:00.876 --> 00:12:04.396
this is the neural soma, and you see basically these long

207
00:12:04.406 --> 00:12:06.685
neurite-like protrusions, which we call tumor microtubules.

208
00:12:06.736 --> 00:12:10.596
What you can see on an ultrastructural basis is that you can

209
00:12:10.676 --> 00:12:14.516
find ribosomes throughout the entire tumor cells with

210
00:12:14.556 --> 00:12:18.456
an enrichment even at the outer tip of these tumor

211
00:12:18.516 --> 00:12:22.320
cells.When you overlay this also again on an RNA

212
00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:26.180
level, you can nicely see that there are also transcripts, again with an

213
00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:30.140
enrichment towards the end, so basically at the growth

214
00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:31.340
cone of these tumor cells.

215
00:12:32.160 --> 00:12:35.800
And lastly, what you can see when you use a puromycin

216
00:12:35.939 --> 00:12:39.900
readout, again indicating actual translation,

217
00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:43.920
you can nicely see that there's also a local translation actually going on

218
00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:45.340
in these neurite-like protrusions.

219
00:12:46.780 --> 00:12:50.580
We can now actually separate also somata

220
00:12:50.940 --> 00:12:54.800
from these neurite-like protrusion using a so-called insert

221
00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.960
assay, and basically sequence these two compartments

222
00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:03.180
separately and then understand what actually differs

223
00:13:03.260 --> 00:13:06.739
in these tumor cells as compared to their somata.

224
00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:11.280
And when doing so and using basically the overexpressed

225
00:13:11.720 --> 00:13:15.300
tumor microtubule genes and really try to basically,

226
00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:19.570
only using the differentially expressed genes, try to recluster these genes, what

227
00:13:19.600 --> 00:13:23.360
we can see is that basically those

228
00:13:23.380 --> 00:13:26.920
genes that are upregulated in the tumor microtubule

229
00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:30.940
are the ones that can define cell states much better than

230
00:13:30.980 --> 00:13:33.200
those that are significantly upregulated

231
00:13:34.140 --> 00:13:36.920
within the soma itself as compared to the TM.

232
00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:41.120
Which shows again that this is a very specialized subcompartment that

233
00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:44.800
is able to identify and also characterize

234
00:13:45.440 --> 00:13:49.400
cell states and cell identity. Again, this is also resembling

235
00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:53.940
work that has been shown during neurodevelopment, where the

236
00:13:54.020 --> 00:13:57.660
neurites can have a completely different molecular composition

237
00:13:58.040 --> 00:14:01.740
than the somata and define actually cell states also in neurons.

238
00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:06.620
And when looking at the specific genes that are upregulated

239
00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:11.180
in tumor microtubules, what we could find, again, is a

240
00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:15.160
molecule called GPM6A as compared to other

241
00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:17.920
genes where we knew that they play a role like GAB43,

242
00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:19.260
and that

243
00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:25.140
GPM6A is a driver of tumor microtubule

244
00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:26.880
formation and invasion. You can nicely see this.

245
00:14:26.890 --> 00:14:30.780
This is a long tumor microtubule, and you see basically here in the purple color,

246
00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:34.940
the GPM6A protrusions that really are formed on top of

247
00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:38.850
these tumor microtubules. And when, again, knocking this down,

248
00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:43.780
what you can nicely see is that, again, tumor invasion is

249
00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:47.700
mainly driven by this GPM6A overexpression.

250
00:14:47.740 --> 00:14:51.700
Again, also a molecule very much involved in dendrite

251
00:14:51.709 --> 00:14:52.370
development,

252
00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:55.340
coming from neuronal development again.

253
00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.780
With this, I would just want to close and hope I could convince you

