There's two manuscripts that we published last year.

1205
01:08:43.044 --> 01:08:45.905
The first author of these papers is sitting here, Masashi Nomura.

1206
01:08:45.945 --> 01:08:47.744
I really like to highlight his work.

1207
01:08:48.324 --> 01:08:51.905
This is a very large cohort that was done in collaboration with many other

1208
01:08:52.044 --> 01:08:55.504
centers. We also have Fulvio D'Angelo from the Yavaroni lab here.

1209
01:08:55.744 --> 01:08:57.964
And Roel Verhaak was also involved.

1210
01:08:57.985 --> 01:09:01.905
And we've really taken 100 samples, done a lot of

1211
01:09:01.945 --> 01:09:05.184
single-nucleus analysis, more than half a million single nuclei.

1212
01:09:05.684 --> 01:09:09.504
And the idea was try to see if with more power, we would come up with the same

1213
01:09:09.544 --> 01:09:13.454
conclusion or different ones. And the very long story very short is that

1214
01:09:14.044 --> 01:09:17.224
the structure that we highlighted is not fundamentally different from the four

1215
01:09:17.284 --> 01:09:19.014
states model. We can just break them

1216
01:09:19.824 --> 01:09:22.004
down in a little bit more granular fashion.

1217
01:09:22.025 --> 01:09:25.244
For example, the mesenchymal-like state is now presented in hypoxia,

1218
01:09:25.304 --> 01:09:29.224
mesenchymal-like, and stress. These are sub flavors of similar programs, but

1219
01:09:29.264 --> 01:09:31.105
it really gives us a little bit more granularity.

1220
01:09:31.164 --> 01:09:33.804
I don't think the architecture is fundamentally different.

1221
01:09:33.924 --> 01:09:37.525
And if I had more than 15 minutes, I would tell you how we've analyzed how these

1222
01:09:37.624 --> 01:09:41.324
programs evolve after therapy. But unfortunately, you'll have to read the

1223
01:09:41.364 --> 01:09:44.784
papers if you want to have those answers or discuss directly with Masashi.

1224
01:09:45.764 --> 01:09:48.485
So I want to discuss a little bit more of the spatial efforts we're currently doing

1225
01:09:48.504 --> 01:09:52.445
in the lab. So as I was mentioning in the short intro, we've done a

1226
01:09:52.485 --> 01:09:56.164
first pass at spatial analysis of glioblastoma a couple of years ago with Itai.

1227
01:09:56.784 --> 01:09:59.464
And for that, we used a regular Visium platform, so

1228
01:10:00.604 --> 01:10:02.534
55 micron capture spot of transcripts.

1229
01:10:03.004 --> 01:10:05.913
And we've coupled that with spatial proteomics, highly multiplexed Codex.

1230
01:10:06.494 --> 01:10:09.814
And the idea was trying to resolve the spatial organization of these cell states.

1231
01:10:10.824 --> 01:10:14.434
And again, just to give you the quick take-home message,

1232
01:10:15.044 --> 01:10:18.404
we found that in areas of the tumors where there is necrosis,

1233
01:10:19.144 --> 01:10:21.244
these tumors tend to be organized by layers.

1234
01:10:22.184 --> 01:10:26.104
And adjacent to this hypoxic necrotic core, you would

1235
01:10:26.164 --> 01:10:29.664
have a lot of mesenchymal-like malignant cells and inflammatory

1236
01:10:30.084 --> 01:10:34.024
myeloid cells that reside there. This would be adjacently

1237
01:10:34.064 --> 01:10:38.054
followed by a kind of angiogenesis hub with vasculature

1238
01:10:38.203 --> 01:10:41.064
and more T and B cells infiltration.

1239
01:10:41.084 --> 01:10:44.884
And then as you get away from that and you get closer to the

1240
01:10:45.644 --> 01:10:49.504
brain parenchyma, you would then have this neurodevelopmental cell state, OPC,

1241
01:10:49.544 --> 01:10:52.204
NPC-like, that then interacts with the brain parenchyma.

1242
01:10:52.804 --> 01:10:54.584
I think the utility of the model is twofold.

1243
01:10:54.984 --> 01:10:57.684
First of all, it's not too surprising that it's organized around necrosis.

1244
01:10:57.814 --> 01:11:01.604
We've known that for many years from pathology, but we now have a better molecular

1245
01:11:01.664 --> 01:11:03.484
understanding of what the organization looks like.

1246
01:11:04.044 --> 01:11:06.773
And also, I'd like to think that we need to think therapeutically of these

1247
01:11:06.784 --> 01:11:09.404
different areas as different neighborhoods that require different strategies.

1248
01:11:09.804 --> 01:11:13.424
I'm pretty convinced that you've heard beautiful work for cancer neuroscience.

1249
01:11:13.464 --> 01:11:16.914
This will be very relevant for this portion of the tumor where there is deep

1250
01:11:16.964 --> 01:11:18.294
interaction with the brain parenchyma.

1251
01:11:18.744 --> 01:11:22.684
But if we want to target other areas, especially the hypoxic areas, that's

1252
01:11:22.704 --> 01:11:26.454
probably unlikely to be the key, and we might need to better

1253
01:11:26.454 --> 01:11:29.584
understand how immunosuppression occurs in those areas for those strategies.

1254
01:11:29.624 --> 01:11:33.614
So you either look at glioblastoma as four different elements by single-cell states

1255
01:11:33.644 --> 01:11:36.984
or different neighborhoods by spatial, but at the end of the day, I think it helps

1256
01:11:37.024 --> 01:11:37.424
frame the

1257
01:11:38.864 --> 01:11:42.654
idea of how we need to tackle this. I want to spend a little bit of time on some of

1258
01:11:42.654 --> 01:11:46.104
our latest effort in more high-resolution spatial analysis.

1259
01:11:46.604 --> 01:11:49.604
These are more vignettes. There's no stories because we're writing the paper, so I

1260
01:11:49.644 --> 01:11:52.974
don't have solid conclusions, but I just want to highlight what we're currently

1261
01:11:53.024 --> 01:11:56.424
doing in the lab just also as a... this idea.

1262
01:11:56.504 --> 01:12:00.044
So this is the new Visium HD platform that I'm sure many of you are familiar with.

1263
01:12:00.364 --> 01:12:03.724
Two-micron capture RNA instead of 55, so much more resolved.

1264
01:12:04.184 --> 01:12:07.744
FFP compatible, so you can really get exquisite morphology from this type of

1265
01:12:07.784 --> 01:12:11.384
analysis because you don't rely on frozen samples anymore, and this is work in the

1266
01:12:11.424 --> 01:12:13.804
lab led by Chris Mount and his team.

1267
01:12:15.024 --> 01:12:18.304
So this is an example. On the left, you have the H&amp;E of a glioblastoma.

1268
01:12:19.104 --> 01:12:22.944
We've color-coded here the pia, so the innermost surface of the meninges.

1269
01:12:23.004 --> 01:12:26.984
You can see how, in this case, you can follow the pia for a certain point, and

1270
01:12:27.004 --> 01:12:29.084
then it's broken at the bottom of the slide.

1271
01:12:29.544 --> 01:12:33.384
And this glioblastoma has actually broken into the subarachnoid space and is

1272
01:12:33.444 --> 01:12:37.264
now growing in that compartment. On the right is the same analysis

1273
01:12:37.324 --> 01:12:41.114
by Visium HD. We've color-coded the level of malignancy present, so anything that's

1274
01:12:41.204 --> 01:12:44.644
red is highly malignant. So these are all the malignant cells, and you can also see

1275
01:12:44.684 --> 01:12:48.594
some malignant cells in the brain parenchyma that otherwise is mostly containing

1276
01:12:48.824 --> 01:12:52.344
normal cells. And so once we have that, we can begin to

1277
01:12:52.404 --> 01:12:56.344
assign a certain genetic structure because these assays cover the whole

1278
01:12:56.424 --> 01:13:00.244
transcriptome, and so we can use the information to reconstruct the copy

1279
01:13:00.304 --> 01:13:04.144
number of the genome. And you can see here that the spots all

1280
01:13:04.204 --> 01:13:06.744
have expected gain of chromosome 7 in red.

1281
01:13:07.154 --> 01:13:09.644
This is a signature genetic event for primary glioblastoma.

1282
01:13:10.044 --> 01:13:13.834
They have a loss of chromosome 10, another signature event, so we know we're

1283
01:13:13.864 --> 01:13:15.204
capturing correctly malignant cells.

1284
01:13:15.664 --> 01:13:18.883
And then we also have subclonal events that occur in this sample.

1285
01:13:19.304 --> 01:13:21.734
And then we can, on the right, spatially map these subclones.

1286
01:13:21.774 --> 01:13:25.564
And so you can see how in the brain parenchyma, all these subclones are mixed.

1287
01:13:25.594 --> 01:13:29.524
And then in the subarachnoid space, we find they're more regionally

1288
01:13:29.564 --> 01:13:31.524
confined, and we see clones

1289
01:13:32.484 --> 01:13:35.664
here, for example, in this area, and then in this area, we have the other clones,

1290
01:13:35.774 --> 01:13:37.204
some of which are a little bit more intermixed.

1291
01:13:37.564 --> 01:13:40.324
But you can see how they're actually quite geographically separated.

1292
01:13:41.884 --> 01:13:45.444
So this is the first type of analysis you can do with this assay.

1293
01:13:45.494 --> 01:13:47.884
The second type of analysis, you can look at expression.

1294
01:13:47.944 --> 01:13:51.764
So in this case, same sample. We now color-coded the expression

1295
01:13:51.844 --> 01:13:54.434
states of malignant cells based on the spatial transcriptomics.

1296
01:13:54.764 --> 01:13:57.404
You can see here the pia. You can see where it's destroyed.

1297
01:13:57.424 --> 01:14:00.984
You can actually now begin to molecularly dissect this area of

1298
01:14:01.024 --> 01:14:04.244
infiltration through the pia, how these cells actually break and infiltrate the

1299
01:14:04.264 --> 01:14:08.144
leptomeningeal space. You can see how the colors, this is all a simplified

1300
01:14:08.204 --> 01:14:12.084
color schematic, but you can see the color of the cells

1301
01:14:12.184 --> 01:14:15.964
changes, and you can see that sometimes it's really a function of the

1302
01:14:16.004 --> 01:14:17.904
distance from a blood vessel. This is a blood vessel.

1303
01:14:18.084 --> 01:14:20.484
Around it, you have specific malignant cell states.

1304
01:14:20.904 --> 01:14:22.724
Further away from it, it's a different one.

1305
01:14:22.764 --> 01:14:26.744
And so sometimes these states are purely a reflection of where they sit in the

1306
01:14:26.764 --> 01:14:30.274
microenvironment. And you can see that in some other instances, actually, this

1307
01:14:30.284 --> 01:14:33.964
doesn't seem to be the case. This is another state, and it's not really dependent

1308
01:14:34.004 --> 01:14:35.144
on the distance from the blood vessel.

1309
01:14:35.464 --> 01:14:38.804
And so it goes back to these questions, how much is genetically dictated?

1310
01:14:38.844 --> 01:14:42.393
How much is microenvironmentally dictated in these type of expression programs that

1311
01:14:42.424 --> 01:14:46.364
we capture? And so here is an example where we see

1312
01:14:46.424 --> 01:14:50.244
both things occurring. So as I've highlighted, the microenvironment

1313
01:14:50.304 --> 01:14:53.834
dictates those cell states. But in this area, you can see it's a specific genetic

1314
01:14:53.904 --> 01:14:57.424
clone. And so this expression state is mostly related to a genetic clone.

1315
01:14:57.464 --> 01:15:01.124
So a lot to disentangle. I'm not claiming we have all the answers, but this is the

1316
01:15:01.144 --> 01:15:04.624
type of effort that we're trying to do now at scale to understand how

1317
01:15:04.664 --> 01:15:07.044
glioblastoma infiltrates in the leptomeningeal space.

1318
01:15:08.264 --> 01:15:12.064
We're doing similar analysis, again, with the same questions, trying to understand

1319
01:15:12.084 --> 01:15:15.504
the relationship between genetics and expression with the group of Dan Landau,

1320
01:15:16.624 --> 01:15:18.334
where we're doing now single-cell multi-omics,

1321
01:15:19.264 --> 01:15:22.964
combining single-cell whole-genome sequencing with single-cell RNA

1322
01:15:22.984 --> 01:15:26.524
sequencing, and we do that in a spatially resolved manner in the tissue.

1323
01:15:26.564 --> 01:15:27.744
We use slide tags, so we

1324
01:15:28.804 --> 01:15:32.453
place spatial tags in the tissue. We recover nuclei that are

1325
01:15:32.484 --> 01:15:36.384
spatially positioned, and then we single-cell whole genomes those nuclei and

1326
01:15:36.424 --> 01:15:38.184
do RNA sequencing from the same cells.

1327
01:15:38.204 --> 01:15:41.254
And the idea is to try to build, again, phylogenetic trees of the evolution of

1328
01:15:41.284 --> 01:15:45.184
these tumors and understand the relationship with the microenvironmental features.

1329
01:15:45.764 --> 01:15:46.504
So this is a

1330
01:15:47.604 --> 01:15:51.384
tree that has been entirely reconstructed based on SNV, so it is purely

1331
01:15:51.424 --> 01:15:55.184
based on point mutation. And you can see that we're doing a

1332
01:15:55.204 --> 01:15:57.363
pretty decent job at building a tree.

1333
01:15:57.374 --> 01:16:00.764
And we know that we're doing a decent job because then we've mapped the copy number

1334
01:16:00.784 --> 01:16:04.384
aberration that were not used to build the tree, and you can see how the clades of

1335
01:16:04.484 --> 01:16:07.884
copy number actually correspond, they cluster together, and so

1336
01:16:07.924 --> 01:16:11.804
the tree makes sense. So we're now doing a lot of work around this.

1337
01:16:11.884 --> 01:16:15.404
You might have heard Dan Landau giving the plenary and analyzing all the

1338
01:16:15.464 --> 01:16:18.004
ecDNA elements that we find in these

1339
01:16:19.104 --> 01:16:22.424
samples. What I would like to highlight in one minute is the idea that

1340
01:16:23.064 --> 01:16:25.394
sometimes, and we are trying to understand how

1341
01:16:25.504 --> 01:16:29.444
generalizable this is, we see that we

1342
01:16:29.484 --> 01:16:31.004
can build those phylogenetic trees,

1343
01:16:32.024 --> 01:16:35.584
and then we can ask of the cell states that I've described,

1344
01:16:37.144 --> 01:16:39.064
how are they distributed once we build those trees?

1345
01:16:39.104 --> 01:16:42.744
And this really gives us direct insight into human samples about

1346
01:16:42.864 --> 01:16:46.564
plasticity versus heritability of cell states and maybe the importance of

1347
01:16:46.584 --> 01:16:49.744
certain cell states in driving the genetic evolution of these tumors.

1348
01:16:49.784 --> 01:16:53.424
You can see here is the most advanced clone in this sample.

1349
01:16:53.774 --> 01:16:55.384
This is the most genetically evolved.

1350
01:16:55.804 --> 01:16:59.364
And you can see at the bottom color-coded the cell states of glioblastoma, and you

1351
01:16:59.404 --> 01:17:03.364
can see how most of the cells that are these genetically advanced are

1352
01:17:03.424 --> 01:17:07.204
in this OPC/NPC-like state. So it doesn't seem to be a random distribution of

1353
01:17:07.264 --> 01:17:11.084
states. So it's quite possible that at least in some samples, specific state

1354
01:17:12.004 --> 01:17:15.324
kind of preferentially evolved the genetics of this tumor.

1355
01:17:15.644 --> 01:17:19.044
And again, we're now going to do this at scale to use the information to

1356
01:17:19.084 --> 01:17:21.904
really assess heritability and plasticity.

1357
01:17:23.264 --> 01:17:27.104
This goes back to what Varun highlighted as well and the beautiful

1358
01:17:27.144 --> 01:17:31.004
work he's done and so Frank Winkler, where these cells, these OPC-like

1359
01:17:31.024 --> 01:17:34.424
cells, might be preferentially responsible for invasion.

1360
01:17:34.654 --> 01:17:38.124
And you can see here in another study we recently published

1361
01:17:38.164 --> 01:17:41.984
where this is a xenograft of these tumors in the mouse brain.

1362
01:17:42.684 --> 01:17:46.604
And we're actually asking what programs allow these cells to cross

1363
01:17:46.614 --> 01:17:50.444
the midline. So you really need to compare the area where the tumor was injected,

1364
01:17:50.484 --> 01:17:52.884
which is here, to the contralateral hemisphere.

1365
01:17:52.904 --> 01:17:56.124
And you can see again that the color distribution is not random.

1366
01:17:56.214 --> 01:17:59.984
Anything that is on the other side of the brain tends to be

1367
01:18:00.024 --> 01:18:03.204
enriched in this bluish-like color, and these are, again, these

1368
01:18:03.244 --> 01:18:07.144
OPC/NPC-like cells, whereas the primary site is enriched in

1369
01:18:07.164 --> 01:18:11.024
different states. And again, in the paper, we develop how perivascular

1370
01:18:11.084 --> 01:18:14.994
invasion programs actually differ from periaxonal invasion programs and

1371
01:18:15.044 --> 01:18:18.404
how these different states that we captured by single-cell RNA sequencing actually

1372
01:18:18.444 --> 01:18:22.044
recapitulate different functions in the tumor and allow the tumor to expand into

1373
01:18:22.084 --> 01:18:25.904
different niches.As always, I have too many slides, so I

1374
01:18:25.984 --> 01:18:29.884
have to stop here because I don't want to be the one running above time

1375
01:18:29.944 --> 01:18:31.924
after telling everyone to stay on time.

1376
01:18:31.964 --> 01:18:35.784
So, just a vignette to say that we're doing similar efforts in IDH mutant

1377
01:18:35.824 --> 01:18:36.284
gliomas,

1378
01:18:37.304 --> 01:18:39.384
both single-cell analysis and spatial.

1379
01:18:40.004 --> 01:18:42.064
These papers are at various press of production.

1380
01:18:43.104 --> 01:18:46.304
And again, a lot of work from Masashi Nomura, who's in the room if you want to

1381
01:18:46.384 --> 01:18:50.264
discuss with him. I can give you maybe the take-home message from the IDH

1382
01:18:50.504 --> 01:18:54.364
mutant progression work that is in press, where we've actually

1383
01:18:54.384 --> 01:18:57.984
looked at the impact of changes in DNA methylation on the cell state hierarchy.

1384
01:18:58.524 --> 01:19:02.394
And what we found is that as methylation decreases, as this tumor advances,

1385
01:19:02.444 --> 01:19:06.204
which is a known phenomenon, we see that that affects the heritability of cell

1386
01:19:06.264 --> 01:19:10.044
states. We see change in differentiation trajectories and fewer

1387
01:19:10.084 --> 01:19:11.504
cells actually achieve differentiation.

1388
01:19:11.544 --> 01:19:14.224
More cells remain in stem-like programs.

1389
01:19:14.544 --> 01:19:18.004
The cell for neural stem cell is enhanced, and so we better understand now the

1390
01:19:18.064 --> 01:19:21.724
impact of hypomethylation on how hypomethylation is actually

1391
01:19:21.964 --> 01:19:25.484
really bad for clinical outcome, and maybe that's through changes in hierarchy.

1392
01:19:26.144 --> 01:19:30.124
And I frequently think that we're too obsessed with cell states, and

1393
01:19:30.164 --> 01:19:34.064
maybe it doesn't matter that much if you want to just try to get a

1394
01:19:34.084 --> 01:19:38.044
clinical handle on these tumors. But actually, when we analyze samples of

1395
01:19:38.204 --> 01:19:42.154
gliomas that respond to the current standard of care, targeted

1396
01:19:42.224 --> 01:19:46.084
therapy against IDH mutation, we see that those

1397
01:19:46.164 --> 01:19:49.584
agents actually affect these differentiation hierarchies.

1398
01:19:49.624 --> 01:19:53.204
Those agents actually do facilitate the differentiation of cancer cells.

1399
01:19:53.244 --> 01:19:55.484
That's probably how the clinical benefit is obtained.

1400
01:19:56.384 --> 01:20:00.324
And if you see that hypomethylation affect the capacity of cells to differentiate,

1401
01:20:00.344 --> 01:20:03.464
you might imagine that you might need to begin to integrate that into

1402
01:20:03.544 --> 01:20:07.244
stratification of patients, because we know that too few patients actually

1403
01:20:07.284 --> 01:20:11.024
respond to these therapies, and the field is trying to understand who will respond

1404
01:20:11.044 --> 01:20:13.384
and who will not respond. With that, I'm done.

1405
01:20:14.024 --> 01:20:17.404
I've already thanked the people along the way, so I'll stop here and thank you for

1406
01:20:17.444 --> 01:20:19.104
your attention and for staying to this session.

1407
01:20:26.064 --> 01:20:29.914
Yeah, fantastic work. Kind of just a question regarding the last part of your

1408
01:20:30.064 --> 01:20:33.563
study, the IDH mutant inhibitor and single-cell

1409
01:20:33.584 --> 01:20:37.504
analysis. Kind of curious, so from your analysis, did you

1410
01:20:37.644 --> 01:20:40.604
see that low-grade oligo or low-grade

1411
01:20:40.904 --> 01:20:44.764
astrocytoma, if both can respond to the treatment?

1412
01:20:44.964 --> 01:20:48.244
Did you see that there some difference in terms of differentiation?

1413
01:20:50.204 --> 01:20:50.304
So-

1414
01:20:50.344 --> 01:20:51.364
Or methylation, yeah.

1415
01:20:51.604 --> 01:20:51.744
Yeah.

1416
01:20:52.564 --> 01:20:55.584
The study actually focused a lot on oligodendrogliomas

1417
01:20:56.384 --> 01:21:00.124
in the response to targeted agent, because that's where we had enough

1418
01:21:00.184 --> 01:21:01.264
power to see

1419
01:21:02.664 --> 01:21:06.164
the signal. We had the challenge, and

1420
01:21:06.484 --> 01:21:10.124
this is more of a comment in general for the field, the challenge is that you will

1421
01:21:10.264 --> 01:21:13.864
see an effect of those agents if you sample and analyze on drug.

1422
01:21:15.244 --> 01:21:18.544
So you need to really get the sample while the patient is still receiving the drug-

1423
01:21:18.804 --> 01:21:18.924
Mm.

1424
01:21:18.994 --> 01:21:21.714
... and then do all this analysis, and you will see this effect of differentiation.

1425
01:21:22.364 --> 01:21:25.944
Anytime we've analyzed gliomas, even if they had a clinical response, but then for

1426
01:21:25.984 --> 01:21:28.524
some reason the patient stopped taking the drug, we can't see anything.

1427
01:21:28.904 --> 01:21:28.913
Mm.

1428
01:21:28.924 --> 01:21:32.444
So in our cohort, unfortunately, the astrocytomas were not so rarely

1429
01:21:32.824 --> 01:21:35.374
off drug, so it wasn't really conclusive.

1430
01:21:36.264 --> 01:21:38.744
And so we made more points about the oligodendroglioma.

1431
01:21:38.804 --> 01:21:42.404
But if you look at the Mellinghoff paper and they have some bulk analysis, if you

1432
01:21:42.444 --> 01:21:45.764
analyze that for the responders, it would seem that the signature that we detect by

1433
01:21:45.804 --> 01:21:48.744
single cell, you would expect to see it in astrocytoma as well.

1434
01:21:48.804 --> 01:21:52.434
And if you look at the breakdown of patients that respond to the targeted agent, it

1435
01:21:52.444 --> 01:21:53.804
does seem to affect both populations.

1436
01:21:53.864 --> 01:21:56.744
So whether you have an oligo or an astro, you should be able to respond.

1437
01:21:57.764 --> 01:21:58.144
Thank you.

1438
01:22:01.164 --> 01:22:04.524
With the risk of monopolizing this microphone, it's a really, really great talk.

1439
01:22:05.004 --> 01:22:08.104
I just wanted to get a clarification around the evolutionary trees when you

1440
01:22:08.144 --> 01:22:10.424
correlated that with the OPC-like state.

1441
01:22:10.764 --> 01:22:14.684
Would that then go essentially sort of against

1442
01:22:14.704 --> 01:22:18.504
that idea that OPC-like state is the sort of initiating state?

1443
01:22:18.584 --> 01:22:22.124
So when you start talking about the cell of origin, would that sort of, kind of

1444
01:22:22.164 --> 01:22:23.324
disprove that?

1445
01:22:24.244 --> 01:22:28.214
No, I don't think that, because, again, here we're analyzing very established and

1446
01:22:28.264 --> 01:22:32.024
advanced tumors, so it's very difficult to make any claim about how it started.

1447
01:22:32.444 --> 01:22:33.364
And also we can only

1448
01:22:34.864 --> 01:22:38.584
say something about what we see. It's unclear that we capture the inception of the

1449
01:22:38.604 --> 01:22:41.644
tumor. What I would say is that this tells us how it's evolving.

1450
01:22:42.004 --> 01:22:42.073
Mm.

1451
01:22:42.604 --> 01:22:45.924
And so at least in a few instances, the evolution doesn't seem to

1452
01:22:45.964 --> 01:22:48.304
be all the random states evolving.

1453
01:22:48.364 --> 01:22:51.584
It seems to be driven specifically by a subset of cells.

1454
01:22:51.604 --> 01:22:51.814
But

1455
01:22:53.144 --> 01:22:57.064
I'm pretty sure it won't be always these cells that are so aggressively evolving

1456
01:22:57.084 --> 01:23:00.524
the tumor, but we certainly see that in some cases it's not completely random.

1457
01:23:00.544 --> 01:23:00.764
And so-

1458
01:23:01.424 --> 01:23:01.434
Mm.

1459
01:23:01.434 --> 01:23:04.824
... it's complex questions, but I do think that we should be very careful

1460
01:23:04.884 --> 01:23:08.224
about making any claims about origin of the tumors we're analyzing, established

1461
01:23:08.264 --> 01:23:08.524
tumors.

1462
01:23:08.833 --> 01:23:09.164
For sure. Thanks.

1463
01:23:10.284 --> 01:23:13.644
Hi. I was curious about the OPC-like dissemination.

1464
01:23:13.734 --> 01:23:17.684
Are there any therapeutic strategies that you think would impact

1465
01:23:17.724 --> 01:23:21.494
OPC-like dissemination or differentiation to prevent this

1466
01:23:21.584 --> 01:23:21.864
state?

1467
01:23:23.184 --> 01:23:25.764
That's a great question. Probably Varun can answer better than I can.

1468
01:23:26.184 --> 01:23:26.264
I

1469
01:23:27.604 --> 01:23:31.584
do think that if we want to block that migration, it's really a neurodevelopmental

1470
01:23:31.664 --> 01:23:33.004
program that we need to target.

1471
01:23:34.124 --> 01:23:38.004
We don't put enough effort into that, but I do think that it's quite clear

1472
01:23:38.044 --> 01:23:41.304
now that this is the distally invasive state.

1473
01:23:41.784 --> 01:23:42.384
And so,

1474
01:23:43.524 --> 01:23:44.564
we're still

1475
01:23:45.384 --> 01:23:47.744
working very hard to dissect all the molecular features.

1476
01:23:48.284 --> 01:23:51.984
I can tell you from another spatial study that we're doing that

1477
01:23:52.304 --> 01:23:56.124
we see that that state also has importance to traverse the gray-white

1478
01:23:56.264 --> 01:23:57.684
junction. The paper is in bioRxiv.

1479
01:23:57.804 --> 01:24:01.564
It seems to be even a functional

1480
01:24:01.584 --> 01:24:05.224
barrier to go between the subcortical white matter and the

1481
01:24:05.264 --> 01:24:05.684
cortex,

1482
01:24:06.504 --> 01:24:09.744
and that might actually relate to the preferential location of

1483
01:24:09.804 --> 01:24:11.504
oligodendroglioma versus astrocytoma.

1484
01:24:11.584 --> 01:24:15.504
So there's still a lot to disentangle, and we're not thinking

1485
01:24:15.584 --> 01:24:18.974
about it enough therapeutically, but obviously that's the goal at some point, but

1486
01:24:19.004 --> 01:24:21.024
we haven't really developed a strategy.

1487
01:24:21.344 --> 01:24:21.564
Thanks.

1488
01:24:21.884 --> 01:24:22.264
Thank you.

1489
01:24:23.964 --> 01:24:24.104
Hi.

1490
01:24:24.124 --> 01:24:24.664
Last question.

1491
01:24:25.264 --> 01:24:29.224
Great studies. I was wondering about the layered and not

1492
01:24:29.284 --> 01:24:33.004
layered tumors organization. You had this study in

1493
01:24:33.064 --> 01:24:37.032
glioblastoma a couple of years ago-Last year, I

1494
01:24:37.092 --> 01:24:40.732
think the Filbin lab looked at it in pediatric ependymomas, and now

1495
01:24:41.412 --> 01:24:43.992
you mentioned also IDH mutant astrocytomas.

1496
01:24:44.022 --> 01:24:47.972
So I was wondering whether you think this sort of layering that you

1497
01:24:48.052 --> 01:24:51.992
see, and you can link it with other patient outcomes or phenotypes, whether

1498
01:24:52.032 --> 01:24:55.632
this is something recurrent on all the brain tumors or

1499
01:24:56.132 --> 01:24:59.232
it's something on IDH mutant or specifically iomas?

1500
01:24:59.712 --> 01:25:02.892
Yeah, no, I do think that you know a lot of the organizational principle will be

1501
01:25:02.952 --> 01:25:04.952
shared by different classes of brain tumors.

1502
01:25:04.982 --> 01:25:07.792
I think they all have to deal with the brain architecture.

1503
01:25:07.802 --> 01:25:09.162
They all have to deal with

1504
01:25:10.692 --> 01:25:12.432
stressors like hypoxia and necrosis.

1505
01:25:12.972 --> 01:25:16.532
So I think a lot of the response, and because of the kind of cellular elements

1506
01:25:16.992 --> 01:25:20.812
are shared, so it's easy to imagine that a lot of this architecture will be

1507
01:25:20.952 --> 01:25:24.592
similar. But it's only

1508
01:25:24.652 --> 01:25:28.232
organized to the extent that there are pressures to organize it.

1509
01:25:28.292 --> 01:25:28.412
So,

1510
01:25:29.572 --> 01:25:31.012
early on when it's like a

1511
01:25:31.832 --> 01:25:35.372
kind of initiating tumor, it's highly structured because of the

1512
01:25:35.392 --> 01:25:37.072
underlying anatomy of the brain.

1513
01:25:38.272 --> 01:25:41.772
As they break down the residual brain anatomy,

1514
01:25:42.312 --> 01:25:45.812
it becomes quite messy and very intertwined and not very

1515
01:25:45.872 --> 01:25:49.472
organized. And it's only later when you have really

1516
01:25:49.532 --> 01:25:53.192
important environmental pressure because they're beginning to run out of

1517
01:25:53.232 --> 01:25:53.692
nutrients-

1518
01:25:54.012 --> 01:25:54.052
Mm

1519
01:25:54.092 --> 01:25:56.012
... that you begin to see another pattern of organization.

1520
01:25:56.052 --> 01:25:59.832
So I don't think it's like, you know throughout the history of the tumor, it will

1521
01:25:59.892 --> 01:26:02.572
always be following a very precise organization.

1522
01:26:02.592 --> 01:26:06.572
It's just, at the beginning and as the necrosis occurs, these are

1523
01:26:06.612 --> 01:26:09.352
very important therapeutic kind of environmental pressures.

1524
01:26:09.912 --> 01:26:12.192
And then throughout, a lot of different scenarios can occur.

1525
01:26:12.832 --> 01:26:15.572
Have you looked also at primary recurrent tumors?

1526
01:26:16.072 --> 01:26:18.472
What's the difference in terms of these layerings?

1527
01:26:18.652 --> 01:26:19.812
So not spatially.

1528
01:26:19.852 --> 01:26:20.052
Okay.

1529
01:26:20.532 --> 01:26:24.052
But, again, in terms of cell state distribution, we've done quite a

1530
01:26:24.472 --> 01:26:28.252
lot of work in terms of how they evolve in primary and recurrence.

1531
01:26:28.632 --> 01:26:30.632
And the take home message is that

1532
01:26:31.872 --> 01:26:35.292
it's frequently different between the primary and recurrence, but it's different in

1533
01:26:35.372 --> 01:26:37.332
ways that most of the time we cannot really predict.

1534
01:26:37.672 --> 01:26:37.972
Mm.

1535
01:26:38.212 --> 01:26:41.932
And so again, there might be a lot of spatial confounders in how these

1536
01:26:43.492 --> 01:26:44.332
